# Lab 2 - Interfaces and Cables

## Lab Objective
Connect network devices together using the correct 
cable types based on device types and distances.
Auto MDI-X is disabled so correct cable selection matters.

## Important Note
Packet Tracer does not differentiate between single-mode 
and multimode fiber but the correct type should be 
considered based on distance.

## Network Topology
Two separate network trees connected through routers
over various distances.

## Devices Used
- 4x Routers (R1, R2, R3, R4)
- 8x Switches (SW1 - SW8)
- 3x PCs (PC1, PC2, PC3)
- 1x Server (SRV1)

## Connections and Cable Types

### Router to Router (Red cables = Fiber)
- R1 to R3 - Gig3/0 to Gig2/0 
  - 3 kilometer distance = Single Mode Fiber
- R1 to R2 - Fa0/0 to Fa0/0 
  - 50 meter distance = Copper Straight-Through
- R3 to R4 - Gig3/0 to Gig3/0 
  - 250 meter distance = Multimode Fiber

### Router to Switch (Copper Straight-Through)
- R2 to SW1 - Fa2/1 to Fa1/1
- R2 to SW2 - Fa1/0 to Fa2/1
- R4 to SW5 - Fa2/1 to Fa1/1
- R4 to SW6 - Fa1/0 to Fa1/2

### Switch to Switch (Copper Crossover)
- SW1 to SW3 - Fa0/1 to Fa1/1
- SW2 to SW4 - Fa0/1 to Fa0/1
- SW5 to SW7 - Fa0/1 to Fa0/1
- SW6 to SW8 - Fa0/1 to Fa1/1

### Switch to PC/Server (Copper Straight-Through)
- SW3 to PC1 - Fa0/1 to Fa0
- SW4 to PC2 - Fa0/1 to Fa0
- SW7 to PC3 - Fa0/1 to Fa0
- SW8 to SRV1 - Fa0/1 to Fa0

## Cable Selection Rules Used
- Router to Router long distance = Fiber Optic
- Router to Switch = Copper Straight-Through
- Switch to Switch = Copper Crossover
- Switch to PC/Server = Copper Straight-Through

## What I Learned
- Distance determines fiber vs copper cable choice
- Similar devices need crossover cables
- Different devices use straight-through cables
- Single mode fiber for longer distances (3km+)
- Multimode fiber for shorter distances (up to 550m)
- Auto MDI-X normally handles cable selection 
  automatically on modern devices


